able, though, the absence of a dose-response effect with
both AcEO and ascorbic acid seems to be confusing.
Indeed, the DPPH test reproducibility is controversial,
since it is limited by its lack of specificity; the DPPH assay
is not a competitive reaction, because the purple color of
the DPPH radical can be easily lost via either hydrogen
atom transfer (HAT) or reduction through single elec-
tron transfer (SET). Otherwise, the steric accessibility
of DPPH radical represent the major limitation of this
test that confers a more accessibility of the small
molecules to the radical site and which may conse-
quently have a higher antioxidant effect. On the other
hand, a large brand of antioxidant compounds with
peroxyl radicals may react slowly or may even be
inert in reaction to DPPH which is a nitrogen radical
in the first place [76, 77]. All these artefacts may
interfere with the actual antioxidant effect of the
AcEO and the ascorbic acid used as reference, which
may blind their effective antioxidant effect and omit
the dose-response efficiency of both substrates. On
